Table 1: HalfCheetahDir Meta-Test Performance.
(a)
HyperX successfully solves this task, while existing meta-learning methods fail.
(b)
Not even an agent with access to the correct belief is able to solve this task without appropriate exploration bonus.
(c)
Both exploration bonuses are necessary to succeed, but different realisations with similar effects (e.g., metaCURE) work as well.
The bonuses can be used with other methods, if they provide an approximate belief (for rh​y​p​e​rsuperscript𝑟ℎ𝑦𝑝𝑒𝑟r^{hyper}) and a way of measuring how good the inference is (for rerrorsuperscript𝑟errorr^{\text{error}}).
references:
Figure 6 shows how the bonuses incentivise the agent to explore, with the red gradient in the background visualising the reward bonus (darker meaning more bonus).
When the agent walks outside the sparse-reward interval and updates its belief, the reward bonus in the opposite direction becomes high since it has not yet visited that area with the updated belief very often.
Table 1 (top) shows that a policy trained with a reward bonus only on the state, r​(s)𝑟𝑠r(s), performs worse.
The reason is that the agent is not incentivised to explore states to the far right after its belief has changed.
Inspection of the learned policies shows that agents trained with a state exploration bonus do go outside the interval, and just return to and stay in the sparse-reward zone if the direction was wrong (see Appendix B.4).

A2.T2.caption:
Table 2: 
Meta-test success rates on the ML1 Meta-World benchmark, for the dense and the sparse reward version.
∗Results taken from Yu et al. (2019).
+Results taken from Zhang et al. (2020).
We ran VariBAD and HyperX for 555 random seeds for dense reach/push, and 202020 seeds for dense pick-place.
VariBAD and HyperX were trained to maximise expected online return within 222 episodes.
The first (few) episodes often includes exploratory actions, yet have higher success rate than existing methods that maximise final episodic return.
For the sparse Pick-Place environment, in brackets we report the number of seeds that learned something.

A3.T4.caption: Table 4: Additional Sparse CheetahDir Results, for different RND hyperparameter settings (averaged over three seeds). w​s​i𝑤𝑠𝑖wsi stands for weight scale initialisation of the fixed random prior network.
references:
To assess how sensitive HyperX to choices of hyperparameters that affect the hyperstate exploration bonus, we evaluated it on a range of different choices, shown in Table 4.
There is little sensitivity to architecture depth and batchsize, as well as to the output dimension of the RND networks.
Performance is stable for learning rates 10−3−10−6superscript103superscript10610^{-3}{-}10^{-6} (possibly because we use the Adam optimiser), but we found that the best frequency (f​r​e​q𝑓𝑟𝑒𝑞freq) at which the RND network is updated to be environment dependent.
Performance is sensitive to the scaling factor (w​s​i𝑤𝑠𝑖wsi in the table) for the initial prior network weights. We used a scaling factor of 101010 in our experiments, and found that too small or too large scaling factors can hurt performance.
An interesting direction for future work is to find more principled ways to guide the choice of the hyperparameters that are particularly sensitive to the exploration and across environments.
